0tim0 wrote:Does this mean that warming was over-estimated before the la Nina? IOW, does this study suggest that the "climate sensitivity" is lower than previously thought. If so, that is the big news here.I remember, years ago, some skeptic suggesting that a lot (he may have said "all") warming we'd seen in the 90s was due to el Nino. Unless I mis-remembered, this is probably a sign that the "mainstream scientists" and "skeptics" should spend more time working together and less time calling each other crooks.--tWrong. The heat content of the combined system is still increasing apace. It's just that the el Nino/la Nina phenomenon allows larger or lesser proportions of the the heat retained to be dumped in atmosphere or ocean in particular intervals. Since water can absorb much more heat than air, even if the total heat energy added to the system goes up by much the same amount each year, it's more well hidden when more of the energy can be directly transfered into water.The 'skeptics' are still completely wrong and nutty since they use this kind of thing to claim 'not a problem' or 'system is countering effects' and such, which are patently false.
