Wheels Of Confusion
Ars Legatus Legionis
Registered: Jan 17, 2009Posts: 10671
Posted: Wed Aug 28, 2013 12:38 pm
0tim0 wrote:Does this mean that warming was over-estimated before the la Nina? No. Because climate sensitivity to CO2 was not determined by picking a single decade or so in which either El Nino or La Nina dominated the short-term data. Climate "skeptics," on the other hand, seem very inclined to pick a decade with a dominant La Nina and say it means sensitivity should be lower. Like the last decade. Quote:I remember, years ago, some skeptic suggesting that a lot (he may have said "all") warming we'd seen in the 90s was due to el Nino.The previous record for warmest global temperature was 1998, which was due entirely to the unusually strong El Nino conditions of that year. But that doesn't explain the pattern of the entire decade, and it certainly doesn't explain the pattern of the entire 100+ years of warming. Over time, La Nina and El Nino events cancel out their effects on the temperature data: the highs offset the lows and the overall pattern is no trend caused by either one. This is why real climate scientists don't base claims of climate sensitivity on a single decade of temperature data. Climate itself is generally determined over periods of 30 years or so, because the year-to-year variation in temperatures is relatively high and short-term forcings like ENSO, volcanoes, and solar cycles work on the timescale of about a decade. By using multiple decades of data as the starting point, you allow these short-term factors to mostly cancel themselves out and reveal the underlying trend. It's necessary to separate the signal from the noise. Quote:Unless I mis-remembered, this is probably a sign that the "mainstream scientists" and "skeptics" should spend more time working together and less time calling each other crooks.The "skeptics" need to spend more time learning what they're talking about and how to do statistics. The real climate scientists have already mastered those things and know best how to apply them to the climate. ooostephen wrote:It hasn't warmed for 15+ years, but the globe is still warming? Surface temperatures haven't risen very much over the last 15 years. But the climate system itself is still warming. 90% of the energy goes into the oceans anyway, and during the last decade or so the deep oceans have stolen an unusually high amount of heat from the atmosphere. We're still packing additional energy into the climate system at the rate of four Hiroshima bombs every second. Quote:The salient point is that none of the models allowed for greater than a 10yr pause in temps, with a 95% certainty.Completely untrue. Climate model runs routinely simulate "pauses" of ten years or greater. We expect such things to happen because over the short term, climate data is noisy and sometimes factors can conspire to make warming seem to pause for a bit. But this does not impact the long-term trend. Quote:Those models were clearly wrong, and all their predictions go out the window.Well you're completely wrong about the models, so your arguments go out the window. But it's actually better to realize that ALL models are wrong, but some are useful. Climate models have consistently proven their reliability, in direct contrast to the nay-sayers' claims about them. You're just looking for any ill-informed excuse to dismiss them because you don't like what they show.*edited to fix links and formatting*
Last edited by Wheels Of Confusion on Wed Aug 28, 2013 12:40 pm
