Posted: Wed Aug 28, 2013 12:51 pm
Wheels Of Confusion wrote:0tim0 wrote:Quote:I remember, years ago, some skeptic suggesting that a lot (he may have said "all") warming we'd seen in the 90s was due to el Nino.The previous record for warmest global temperature was 1998, which was due entirely to the unusually strong El Nino conditions of that year. But that doesn't explain the pattern of the entire decade, and it certainly doesn't explain the pattern of the entire 100+ years of warming. More to the point -- you can correct for the effect of La Nina/El Nino, plus other variables like solar output. You take out all the spikes and dips from all these effects, and you get a powerful warming trend that has only accelerated in the last decades.Fundamentally the CO2 greenhouse gas hypothesis is that the excess* CO2 in the atmosphere means that the earth retains more heat, and thus is warmer, than it would be without that excess. Both the models and reality are in solid agreement on this.* Obviously this doesn't apply just to the "excess" and the truth of this hypothesis is the only reason our planet is habitable, which is why it's so silly from the get-go to argue that increasing the amount of greenhouse gasses won't increase the equilibrium temperature.
