0tim0 wrote:Does this mean that warming was over-estimated before the la Nina? IOW, does this study suggest that the "climate sensitivity" is lower than previously thought. If so, that is the big news here.I remember, years ago, some skeptic suggesting that a lot (he may have said "all") warming we'd seen in the 90s was due to el Nino. Unless I mis-remembered, this is probably a sign that the "mainstream scientists" and "skeptics" should spend more time working together and less time calling each other crooks.--tI call it scientific bullying or browbeating. The intent is to intimidate and silence opposition. Scientific progress without question, is enhanced by increased scrutiny. Scientists with integrity should welcome thoughtful criticisms without regard to, or in spite of motive (which may in many cases be unknowable).You cannot control reactions against a well-conceived position, no matter how shocking it may be to your sensibilities. You can, however control your response (making the message more "listenable"). Scientists need to focus on data, not personalities, recognizing the possibility of a wide latitude of interpretations that can run counter to any number of preconceived notions. This is true in all branches of science, but especially true in emerging fields that rely heavily upon models.
