Posted: Wed Aug 28, 2013 1:02 pm
Not to wax nostalgic on y'all, but Entergy has announced it will shutdown Vermont Yankee at the end of next year. This 600 MW BWR supplies nearly three-fourths of Vermont's electricity. Vermont Yankee went online in November 1972 and recently received a 20 year extension from NRC for its operating license. But it is not economically competitive with cut-rate natural gas and irrationally subsidized wind. Replacing VY's 600 MW(e) with natural gas will emit 2.5 million tonnes CO2 each year. 600 MW(e) with 90% capacity factor would need 810 2MW wind turbines at 33% capacity factor. NPP and wind both need 100% backup -- with nuclear you need it much less often but for longer intervals when you do. In three years levelized cost of wind will be about $97/MWh, CCGT about $63/MWh, 2009 dollars. Wind's current $22/MWh pre-tax PTC makes the two LCOE sorta kinda equivalent (as it amounts to an after-tax $33). These levelized costs are marginal costs of wind at its current low penetration of 3.4%. Cost of wind are projected to increase by at least 50% at total renewable penetration of 72%. But no one is planning for that.Sources: True Cost of Coal Power and NREL Renewable Energy Futures Study
